comparison of legislative texts

Nadia Napolano

2024-03-24

The objective of this analysis is to compare the constitutional texts or texts establishing the fundamental rights of the citizen of 4 countries and the European Union.

The hypothesis on which this study is based is that traces of each country’s culture and history can be found in the main legislative texts of each country. We begin by obtaining the data through data harvesting strategies.

These words do not surprise me; the Italian Constitution, written in 1948, is divided into two parts: the first is about the principles of the state and the rights and duties of the citizen, while the second explains concretely how the republic functions. Therefore, I will try to filter the first 54 articles to get the initial part, which in my opinion can give excellent insights. The last word is progressivity of the first part, line 135.

testoit_df_principles <- testoit_df |> 
  filter(line <= 135)
testoit_df_principles |> 
  count(word, sort = TRUE) |> 
  filter(n > 5) |> 
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) |> 

  ggplot(aes(n, word)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(y = NULL)

In the text we find words that refer to the socialist party such as: labor and workers. This is not surprising since the constitution was written after the fascist dictatorship and after World War II, this also explains the words equal and free. I was expecting words like peace, war or women which are not mentioned as often instead. I am very curious to see the analysis of Spain, a European country that wrote the constitution in 1972 after the end of the Franco dictatorship.

South Africa I chose this country because I was very curious to see what kind of differences there might be between very distinct countries with very different backgrounds and histories. The Constitution of South Africa (Constitution of South Africa), formulates the law of the state of South Africa. It provides the legal basis for the existence of the republic, establishes the human rights and duties of citizens, and defines the structure of government.

The current constitution, the country’s fifth, was drafted by South Africa’s parliament elected in 1994 at a general election, the first with universal suffrage and without racial discrimination. It was promulgated by President Nelson Mandela on December 18, 1996, and actually came into effect on February 4, 1997.

Compared to the previous two texts, I would like to emphasize that this text refers to the rights and principles of the country. The words that are repeated the most are right the person and freedom, even before law. The South African constitution has completely different words from Spain and Italy, which were more similar. It talks about time, child, care, health, nature, fair, equitable. And there is also a word that I consider splendid: dignity.

Sentiment analysis

Let’s try to see if there is any positive or negative path in this law texts.

Italy

library(textdata)
library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

merged_df <- testoit_df %>%
  left_join(get_sentiments("bing"), by = c("word" = "word")) %>%
  filter(!is.na(sentiment))  

top_words <- merged_df %>%
  count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%
  slice_max(n, n = 25)

top_words <- top_words %>%
  mutate(word = reorder(word, n))
top_words <- merge(top_words, merged_df, by = "word")


# Create the graph!
ggplot(top_words, aes(x = n, y = word, fill = sentiment)) +
  geom_col() +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("positive" = "green", "negative" = "red")) + 
  labs(y = NULL) +
  theme_minimal()

There are many words that are considered neutral in the text, but overall I would say that it is the positive sentiment that prevails.

Looking for words

lista_dataframes <- list(testoes_df = testoes_df,
                         testoit_df = testoit_df,
                         testoue_df = testoue_df,
                         testoUSA_df = testoUSA_df,
                         testoSA_df = testoSA_df)

words_searched <- c("ethnicity", "love", "hate")

# new vector
results <- vector(mode = "list", length = length(lista_dataframes))


for (word in words_searched) {
  # looking for the word
  for (i in seq_along(lista_dataframes)) {
    df <- lista_dataframes[[i]]
    present <- word %in% df$word
    repetition<- sum(df$word == word)
    results[[i]] <- list(word = word, present = present, repetition = repetition)
  }

  # the results dataframe
  risultati_df <- data.frame(Dataframe = names(lista_dataframes),
                             word = word,
                             Present = sapply(results, function(x) x$present),
                             Repetition = sapply(results, function(x) x$repetition))

  #the barplot
  print(ggplot(risultati_df, aes(x = Dataframe, y = Repetition, fill = Present)) +
          geom_bar(stat = "identity") +
          scale_fill_manual(values = c("red", "green"), labels = c("absent", "present")) +
          labs(x = "Dataframe", y = "number of repetition", fill = "presence of the word") +
          theme_minimal() +
          geom_text(aes(label = Repetition), vjust = -0.5, color = "black") + 
          ggtitle(paste("word:", word)))  
}

I am romantic so i was curious of knowing if the word “love” was in any of the text, but apparently it is not the love that pushes the law; than i look for another strong word: “hate”, this word was absent too; and then “ethnicity”, that was written only in the Constitution of South Africa. This is explained by the story of that Country, who faced the apartheid since 1948 until 1991.

Only the EU Text doesn’t use the word “war”, but seems incredible that in the USA declaration of independence it is repeated ten times.The word “peace” is used less times than the word “war”, maybe it was considered less impactful. THe word “president” surprised me a lot, in the Text of USA it is repeated 122 times, this make sense if we think how much importance and relevance and power the president us there. Then i looked for the “art”, i was wishing that my country, who owes a lot to its art, had given some credit to it in its Constitution, and they did it! as well as the European Union and in Usa’s declaration too. ## N-grams An n-gram is a sequence of n adjacent symbols in particular order. bigram graph

Graphs to represent the relationship between words in texts and their “laws of attraction.”

I created a function to make automatic the process.

library(tidyr)
library(dplyr)
library(ggraph)  #package for bigram network's relationship
library(grid)

create_bigram_graph <- function(df, min_occurrences = 5, num_top_words = 10) {
  # Separate the bigram column into two columns word1 and word2
  df <- df %>%
    separate(bigram, into = c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ")
  
  # Count the occurrences of bigrams
  bigram_counts <- df %>% 
    count(word1, word2, sort = TRUE)
  
  # Filter bigrams with a number of occurrences greater than the minimum value
  bigram_for_graph <- bigram_counts %>%
    filter(n > min_occurrences)
  
  # Use ggraph to create the graph
  set.seed(2020)
  a <- grid::arrow(type = "closed", length = unit(.15, "inches"))
  g <- ggraph(bigram_for_graph, layout = "fr") +
    geom_edge_link(aes(edge_alpha = n), show.legend = FALSE,
                   arrow = a, end_cap = circle(.07, 'inches')) +
    geom_node_point(color = "lightblue", size = 5) +
    geom_node_text(aes(label = name), vjust = 1, hjust = 1) +
    theme_void()
  
  return(g)
}

# Usage of the function to create the graph
bigram_graph <- create_bigram_graph(es_bigrams, min_occurrences = 3)
bigram_graph

Recall that Spain is the only chosen territorial entity of a monarchical nature; this explains the frequent presence of words such as “king,” “crown,” and “prince,” which are connected in the graph by the number of times they appear together. Italy

## `.groups` argument.

  group_by(country) %>%
  mutate(term_frequency = n / sum(n))

I would like to specify that I am aware that the European Union is not a country, the use of the term “country” in this case is improper and has only a functional purpose.

The European text is distinguished by the use of “union” and “nations” as well as “levels.” Going a bit to highlight its role as a union of countries with a common purpose.

Italy is recognized by terms such as “school,” “fulfillment,” and “republic.” I was surprised by the word “school,” apparently in other legal texts it plays a less prominent role.

The Spanish text would seem to be a text about Spain for Spain’s sake, the distinguishing words are all centered on the country itself.

The South African text retains in its distintino aspect the “past” and somewhat obscure words that explain its history: “unfair” and “silent.”

The U.S. text summarizes the country’s political power.

Sparsity

calculate_sparsity <- function(df) {
  library(dplyr)
  
  # Count the frequency of each word
  word_counts <- df %>%
    count(word)
  
  # Calculate the total number of words
  total_words <- sum(word_counts$n)
  
  # Calculate the number of unique words
  unique_words <- nrow(word_counts)
  
  # Calculate the sparsity
  sparsity <- 1 - (unique_words / total_words)
  
  # Return the sparsity value
  return(sparsity)
}
calculate_sparsity(testoes_df)
## [1] 0.7512345
calculate_sparsity(testoit_df)
## [1] 0.6836915
calculate_sparsity(testoSA_df)
## [1] 0.5695067
calculate_sparsity(testoUSA_df)
## [1] 0.6432828
calculate_sparsity(testoue_df)
## [1] 0.5518764

The higher the sparsity, the more different the words in the text and the less they are repeated. This may indicate greater lexical variety in the text; therefore, the Spanish text shows greater linguistic breadth than the others (although we must consider that the analysis is not done on the original language text).

The analysis was very challenging for me to do, and I was able to learn a lot. I hope the results are worthwhile and can provide consistency.
